MOTION TO SUPPLEMENT RECORD WITH EVIDENCE OF RETALIATION BY ADMINISTRATIVE JUDGE JAMES WEST AND FORMAL NOTICE OF APPELLEES' NON-APPEARANCE

Plaintiff-Appellant Marvin D. Tutt, proceeding pro se and in forma pauperis, respectfully moves this Court to supplement the appellate record with critical evidence discovered after the filing of Appellant's Emergency Motion for Injunctive Relief (Dkt. Entry 7).

This motion serves three purposes:

    Supplements the record with evidence of ongoing retaliation and technical obstruction by the state judiciary;

    Provides formal notice that Appellees have failed to appear in this appeal despite proper service; and

    Demonstrates that the systematic coordination and bad faith alleged throughout Appellant's filings continue unabated.

I. FORMAL NOTICE OF APPELLEES' NON-APPEARANCE

As of the filing of this motion, no Appellee has entered an appearance in this appeal.

Service was completed as follows:

    November 17, 2025: Appellant mailed paper copies of the Opening Brief and Emergency Motion to all Appellees via first-class mail, as required by Fed. R. App. P. 25(b).

    November 18, 2025: Appellant filed a Notice of Corrected Service with this Court.

Current Status:

    Appellant's Opening Brief (105 pages) remains unrebutted.

    Appellant's Emergency Motion (documenting systematic obstruction) remains unopposed.

    No Appellee has filed a Notice of Appearance.

Appellant provides this formal notice consistent with Fed. R. App. P. procedures. Appellant reserves the right to seek appropriate relief, including sanctions and entry of default, if Appellees' willful non-appearance continues.

II. SUPPLEMENTAL EVIDENCE: ADMINISTRATIVE ORDER 2025-05

A. Overview On November 17, 2025‚Äîone day after Appellant filed the pending Emergency Motion documenting systematic obstruction‚ÄîAppellant was served with Administrative Order 2025-05, issued by Circuit Court Administrative Judge James H. West.

This Order:

    Makes adjudicated factual findings without providing notice or hearing;

    Was strategically timed to obstruct Appellant's court access;

    Was concealed from the public docket despite wide distribution; and

    Create a state-sponsored "impossibility of compliance."

B. The Order Was Concealed from the Public Docket Maryland Case Search (the state's official public case database) for Case No. C-08-FM-22-000821 shows:

    ‚úì All case events through October 15, 2025

    ‚úó No entry for Administrative Order 2025-05 (October 27)

    ‚úó No entry for service of Order (November 17)

The Order was distributed to federal agencies (Judicial Threat Management Center) and local law enforcement but hidden from the public record. This demonstrates consciousness of guilt regarding the Order's lack of due process.

C. Procedural Due Process Violation The Order imposes severe restrictions (Sheriff escort, ban on communication) based on factual findings ("threatening behavior") without affording Appellant notice or a hearing, in violation of Mathews v. Eldridge.

III. NEW EVIDENCE: ACTIVE TECHNICAL OBSTRUCTION

A. State-Created "Impossibility of Compliance" Administrative Order 2025-05 explicitly mandated that Appellant must communicate regarding court access via email to CCCharlesCtAdmin@mdcourts.gov.

    The Attempt: On November 17, 2025, at 5:30 PM, Appellant attempted to comply with the Order by sending a formal notice of receipt via the mandated email address.

    The Block: The State of Maryland's court servers rejected the connection specifically from Appellant‚Äôs email address.

        Server Response: [mdcourts.com... timed out]

        Error: "The recipient server did not accept our requests to connect."

    Argument: This is a digital "brick wall." The State ordered Appellant to use a specific digital channel and then technically blocked that channel. This creates a legal Impossibility of Compliance and serves as evidence of a bad-faith attempt to manufacture a contempt charge (entrapment).

B. Disproof of "Security Threat" Narrative (First Amendment) The Order justifies restrictions by claiming Appellant is a "threat." Appellant‚Äôs conduct immediately following service of the Order disproves this:

    Appellant posted reviews on a public forum (Google Reviews) regarding the judges involved.

    One review was critical (political speech); one review was complimentary ("exemplary judge").

    This demonstrates Appellant is engaging in protected First Amendment advocacy, not dangerous conduct. The State's characterization of this behavior as "harassment" is pretextual.

IV. CONCLUSION AND RELIEF REQUESTED

The Administrative Order and the subsequent technical blocking of Appellant's email prove that the State Judiciary is not a neutral tribunal but an active adversary engaging in retaliation.

